1
00:00:20,370 --> 00:00:21,701
[WOMAN SOBBING]

2
00:00:21,871 --> 00:00:23,862
[INDISTINCT, LOW CHATTER]

3
00:00:27,243 --> 00:00:29,143
MAN:
Hey, Jeffrey. How are you?

4
00:00:29,312 --> 00:00:31,303
WOMAN:
Hey, Jeffrey.

5
00:00:36,853 --> 00:00:38,650
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

6
00:00:41,658 --> 00:00:43,125
Will you excuse me?

7
00:00:44,627 --> 00:00:46,458
[SEYMOUR CLEARS THROAT]

8
00:00:47,230 --> 00:00:49,460
That looks like a powerful scope.

9
00:00:49,866 --> 00:00:51,493
It was my dad's.

10
00:00:52,769 --> 00:00:56,170
I can't tell you how many times
I found your dad right here...

11
00:00:56,339 --> 00:01:00,366
...right here, sitting there
looking through that thing.

12
00:01:02,679 --> 00:01:04,772
Seymour...

13
00:01:04,948 --> 00:01:06,779
...if I can lose my dad...

14
00:01:06,950 --> 00:01:10,818
...then what's to say
I can't lose my mom too?

15
00:01:12,989 --> 00:01:16,481
I don't know why
this thing happened, kid...

16
00:01:16,693 --> 00:01:18,888
...but I do know your father loved you.

17
00:01:19,362 --> 00:01:23,856
And I'm sure he's up there
right now watching out for you.

18
00:01:26,569 --> 00:01:28,730
You do right by him, Jeffrey.

19
00:01:29,305 --> 00:01:31,637
You look after your mother...

20
00:01:31,808 --> 00:01:35,175
...and you become a man
that he would be proud of.

21
00:01:35,345 --> 00:01:36,835
[CHAIN BREAKS]

22
00:01:37,013 --> 00:01:39,413
-What happened? Are you all right?
-Yeah, I'm okay.

23
00:01:39,582 --> 00:01:42,312
Don't worry, you've got plenty of time.
You'll get there.

24
00:01:50,727 --> 00:01:52,718
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

25
00:01:54,531 --> 00:01:55,555
WOMAN:
Bye, honey!

26
00:01:55,732 --> 00:01:57,393
[HORN HONKS]

27
00:02:00,436 --> 00:02:02,768
STUDENT:
Hey, where you going?

28
00:02:02,939 --> 00:02:04,304
Kiss your mom goodbye?

29
00:02:12,482 --> 00:02:13,847
STUDENTS:
Oh!

30
00:02:14,017 --> 00:02:15,507
[STUDENTS LAUGHING, CHATTERING]

31
00:02:15,685 --> 00:02:17,676
[PANTING, GRUNTING]

32
00:02:18,121 --> 00:02:19,145
[BONE CRUNCHING]

33
00:02:19,322 --> 00:02:20,311
Ooh.

34
00:02:20,490 --> 00:02:21,957
[JEFFREY SOBBING]

35
00:02:22,659 --> 00:02:23,853
What a loser.

36
00:02:29,098 --> 00:02:30,326
[CHUCKLES LIGHTLY]

37
00:02:33,970 --> 00:02:34,959
[BOY LAUGHS]

38
00:02:35,138 --> 00:02:36,833
What do you call that?

39
00:02:43,313 --> 00:02:45,474
Oh, my God.

40
00:03:05,635 --> 00:03:06,897
[GASPS]

41
00:03:08,404 --> 00:03:09,666
Oh.

42
00:03:12,208 --> 00:03:14,039
Jeffrey?

43
00:03:14,777 --> 00:03:16,574
-Jeffrey?
JEFFREY: What do you want?

44
00:03:16,746 --> 00:03:19,772
JAN:
It's Jean-Paul. Something's wrong.

45
00:03:19,949 --> 00:03:22,417
It's just like he's, you know,
like not normal.

46
00:03:22,585 --> 00:03:24,553
Just not normal.

47
00:03:25,755 --> 00:03:27,950
For the love of Mike, what happened?

48
00:03:28,124 --> 00:03:30,490
JAN:
He was just like this when I found.... Oh....

49
00:03:30,660 --> 00:03:33,060
There you go, Jean-Paul.
It's gonna be okay.

50
00:03:33,229 --> 00:03:36,289
Sure it is, sure it is, yeah.

51
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:38,662
Oh.

52
00:03:39,769 --> 00:03:42,636
-No.
-Oh, Jeffrey. Oh, Jeffrey.

53
00:03:42,805 --> 00:03:46,297
Oh, sweetie. Don't-- Jeffrey.

54
00:03:46,809 --> 00:03:48,037
JAN:
Oh.

55
00:03:48,745 --> 00:03:51,043
That's nice for Jean-Paul.

56
00:03:54,550 --> 00:03:58,748
Well, oh, dear. Tsk. Bye-bye.

57
00:03:58,922 --> 00:04:01,117
Let's go, sweetie.

58
00:04:01,291 --> 00:04:04,419
Sometimes it takes a great tragedy...

59
00:04:04,594 --> 00:04:07,062
...to make a man see his life clearly.

60
00:04:08,932 --> 00:04:12,766
I realize in my 29 years on this planet...

61
00:04:12,936 --> 00:04:17,373
...I haven't told you often enough
how much I appreciate you.

62
00:04:17,540 --> 00:04:23,775
But you are all I have left
in this cruel world.

63
00:04:24,347 --> 00:04:28,579
And I'm not going to let anything
come between us.

64
00:04:28,751 --> 00:04:30,742
-Oh....
-Ever.

65
00:04:31,621 --> 00:04:35,182
-I love you.
-I love you too.

66
00:04:36,426 --> 00:04:38,587
Thank you, sweetie, love you.

67
00:04:38,761 --> 00:04:41,855
But you know what, honey?
We really have to get going, we're late.

68
00:04:42,198 --> 00:04:43,825
MAN:
I can see that my time is almost up.

69
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,468
So I want to share with you
one final story.

70
00:04:46,636 --> 00:04:50,800
On a beautiful morning in 1998...

71
00:04:50,974 --> 00:04:54,000
...I went to my doctor
for a routine colonoscopy.

72
00:04:54,177 --> 00:04:58,307
He ran some tests to make sure
I didn't have cancer...

73
00:04:58,481 --> 00:05:00,039
...but I did.

74
00:05:00,216 --> 00:05:01,615
[AUDIENCE GASPING]

75
00:05:02,218 --> 00:05:05,210
I tried every treatment
known to Western medicine...

76
00:05:09,859 --> 00:05:13,727
...and some unknown
to Western medicine.

77
00:05:14,030 --> 00:05:16,021
[CHUCKLING, CHATTERING]

78
00:05:17,233 --> 00:05:19,292
Whoo! Ha-ha-ha.

79
00:05:20,636 --> 00:05:22,763
Nothing worked.

80
00:05:23,473 --> 00:05:26,306
[VOICE BREAKING]
I was told I was....

81
00:05:26,909 --> 00:05:30,777
I was told I was going to die
in six months.

82
00:05:31,914 --> 00:05:34,781
That was six years ago.

83
00:05:34,951 --> 00:05:37,476
I beat cancer.

84
00:05:38,921 --> 00:05:40,582
How?

85
00:05:40,757 --> 00:05:42,281
With my mind.

86
00:05:42,458 --> 00:05:45,791
I decided I was not gonna let
some overactive clump of cells...

87
00:05:45,962 --> 00:05:48,226
...stop me from living my life.

88
00:05:48,398 --> 00:05:53,563
From that moment on, I realized
I could have anything my heart desired.

89
00:05:53,736 --> 00:05:55,203
You can too.

90
00:05:55,371 --> 00:05:59,569
Remember, you are the author
of your own life story.

91
00:05:59,742 --> 00:06:03,473
Why not make it a happy ending?
Thank you.

92
00:06:03,646 --> 00:06:05,637
[APPLAUSE]

93
00:06:07,183 --> 00:06:08,707
JAN:
Oh.

94
00:06:12,855 --> 00:06:14,948
[ROCK SONG PLAYING OVER HEADPHONES]

95
00:06:15,124 --> 00:06:17,718
[MOUTHS]
<i>One, two, three, four!</i>

96
00:06:31,908 --> 00:06:33,899
[CD SKIPPING]

97
00:06:34,077 --> 00:06:37,444
-Son-of-a--
-Good morning, Jeffrey.

98
00:06:37,613 --> 00:06:41,344
That's Mr. Mannus to you,
and there's nothing good about it.

99
00:06:41,517 --> 00:06:43,212
Jeffrey...

100
00:06:44,454 --> 00:06:46,979
...did you change the window display?

101
00:06:48,925 --> 00:06:51,052
JEFFREY:
Sex sells, Seymour.

102
00:06:51,227 --> 00:06:53,889
Change it back, now!

103
00:06:54,063 --> 00:06:56,429
I'm putting Keith in charge
of window displays.

104
00:06:56,599 --> 00:06:59,363
-What?
-I need someone I can count on.

105
00:06:59,535 --> 00:07:02,629
Seymour, how long
have I been employed here?

106
00:07:02,805 --> 00:07:04,067
Thirteen years.

107
00:07:04,240 --> 00:07:07,403
Yeah. And in all that time,
have I ever missed a day of work?

108
00:07:07,577 --> 00:07:11,775
Yes. More than any employee I ever had.

109
00:07:11,948 --> 00:07:14,576
There was the day your ant farm broke...

110
00:07:14,750 --> 00:07:18,686
...the day you lost your hat,
the day you had a sore tongue.

111
00:07:18,855 --> 00:07:21,585
I can't do my job if I can't enunciate.

112
00:07:21,757 --> 00:07:23,884
Jeffrey, I like you.

113
00:07:24,060 --> 00:07:26,722
I liked your father,
he was a good friend...

114
00:07:26,896 --> 00:07:29,057
...and a great Rotarian.

115
00:07:29,232 --> 00:07:32,759
But I need you to start
taking this job seriously.

116
00:07:33,769 --> 00:07:37,398
Just behave or you're fired.

117
00:07:37,573 --> 00:07:39,598
MERT:
You know, positivity goes back centuries.

118
00:07:39,775 --> 00:07:44,109
I mean, Jesus, Jesus, for crying out loud,
was a motivational speaker.

119
00:07:44,280 --> 00:07:45,907
-I mean, at his core.
-I guess, yeah.

120
00:07:46,082 --> 00:07:47,106
--talk to him.

121
00:07:47,283 --> 00:07:50,218
I haven't done anything like that in years.
What do I say to him?

122
00:07:50,386 --> 00:07:54,618
Just ask him a question. You could
ask him a follow-up about his colon.

123
00:07:54,790 --> 00:07:58,123
This is utterly ridiculous.
I have a lot of work to do. I'm just gonna--

124
00:07:58,294 --> 00:08:00,558
Ask him anything,
because here's the point:

125
00:08:00,730 --> 00:08:03,893
You can't spend
the rest of your Friday nights...

126
00:08:04,066 --> 00:08:06,034
...playing Scrabble with that son of yours.

127
00:08:06,202 --> 00:08:08,727
-I know.
-You gotta dip your toe in the water.

128
00:08:08,905 --> 00:08:11,897
Somehow, some way,
some dipping must occur.

129
00:08:12,074 --> 00:08:14,065
Stop talking about-- Okay, okay.

130
00:08:14,243 --> 00:08:16,643
-Calm down, relax. It'll be easy.
-Okay, I'm mature.

131
00:08:16,812 --> 00:08:19,337
The third world's a region
I'd like to get my hands on.

132
00:08:19,515 --> 00:08:22,006
-They could use some positivity.
-Hi.

133
00:08:22,185 --> 00:08:23,777
-Hi.
-Excuse me, gentlemen.

134
00:08:23,953 --> 00:08:26,444
-H--
-Hi.

135
00:08:27,623 --> 00:08:30,786
I don't want to interrupt anything,
of course, but I was wondering...

136
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:35,021
-...if it's all right if I ask you a question?
-Sure. Absolutely.

137
00:08:37,833 --> 00:08:40,529
Stem cells, that's what I mean.

138
00:08:40,703 --> 00:08:45,037
It's like, what do you think of the stem-cell
research that's going on today?

139
00:08:46,275 --> 00:08:49,369
I'm no expert, but I think
if it helps the human race, go for it.

140
00:08:49,545 --> 00:08:51,103
[CHUCKLES]
Good. Good answer.

141
00:08:51,280 --> 00:08:52,941
[CHUCKLES]
Oh. Thank you.

142
00:08:53,115 --> 00:08:55,140
-Jan Mannus, right?
-Me. Yes, I'm Jan.

143
00:08:55,318 --> 00:08:58,845
Associate Director of Human Resources.
You are doing a hell of a job.

144
00:08:59,021 --> 00:09:00,818
Thank you for noticing.

145
00:09:00,990 --> 00:09:03,049
-Hmm.
-Anyway....

146
00:09:03,226 --> 00:09:04,557
[CLICKING TONGUE]

147
00:09:04,727 --> 00:09:07,992
-Okay.
-Do you like, uh, jazz?

148
00:09:08,164 --> 00:09:09,188
Yes.

149
00:09:09,365 --> 00:09:10,764
-Do you?
-I love jazz.

150
00:09:10,933 --> 00:09:12,992
You lo--?
Well, I play in a band...

151
00:09:13,169 --> 00:09:17,868
...and we gig on Friday nights
at the Jazz Odyssey.

152
00:09:18,040 --> 00:09:19,268
Yes, I know that place.

153
00:09:19,442 --> 00:09:22,070
Do you? Good.
Would you like to come with me?

154
00:09:22,245 --> 00:09:25,180
I'd love to come with you.
That's the most wonderful invitation.

155
00:09:25,348 --> 00:09:26,838
-Thank you.
-Terrific.

156
00:09:27,950 --> 00:09:31,818
But I'm afraid I can't on Friday night.

157
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:35,890
-I'm sorry. What did you say?
-I said I can't make it Friday night.

158
00:09:36,058 --> 00:09:37,753
I'm still not understanding you...

159
00:09:37,927 --> 00:09:40,862
...because the word "can't"
isn't in my vocabulary.

160
00:09:41,097 --> 00:09:42,758
[BOTH LAUGH]

161
00:09:42,932 --> 00:09:47,232
You see, Jan, we never regret
the things in life we do...

162
00:09:47,403 --> 00:09:50,566
...only the things we don't.

163
00:09:51,407 --> 00:09:53,466
-I wrote that.
-Ah.

164
00:09:54,010 --> 00:09:55,034
I do.

165
00:09:55,244 --> 00:09:57,041
[BOTH LAUGH]

166
00:09:57,213 --> 00:10:00,080
I do, but you know what I mean,
not like the whole "I do."

167
00:10:00,249 --> 00:10:01,773
I mean, what I'm saying is yes.

168
00:10:01,951 --> 00:10:04,681
I would like to go with you...

169
00:10:04,854 --> 00:10:07,982
...and listen to you play the jazz.

170
00:10:08,691 --> 00:10:10,682
[VIDEO GAME PLAYING]

171
00:10:12,028 --> 00:10:14,519
-Hi, sweetheart.
-What are you doing here?

172
00:10:14,697 --> 00:10:16,597
I thought I'd give you a ride home.

173
00:10:16,766 --> 00:10:20,725
Guess who I ran into yesterday?
Jennifer Cushman's mother.

174
00:10:20,903 --> 00:10:23,167
Jennifer Cushman
is apparently getting a divorce.

175
00:10:23,339 --> 00:10:24,772
-Good for her.
-I know.

176
00:10:24,940 --> 00:10:29,343
She'll be at the church's single mixer
on Friday so I thought you might wanna go.

177
00:10:29,512 --> 00:10:31,537
I have plans with you Friday night,
remember?

178
00:10:31,714 --> 00:10:32,976
Oh, right.

179
00:10:33,149 --> 00:10:36,118
Why are you so concerned
about my personal life all of a sudden?

180
00:10:36,285 --> 00:10:39,812
You haven't been on a date in three years,
Jeffrey. I'm concerned about--

181
00:10:39,989 --> 00:10:41,513
Neither have you.

182
00:10:41,691 --> 00:10:43,352
Well, I got asked out today, and....

183
00:10:43,526 --> 00:10:46,495
-Pfft. Please.
-What do you mean, "Please"?

184
00:10:46,662 --> 00:10:49,062
Can you--?
What is wrong with me getting asked out?

185
00:10:49,231 --> 00:10:51,358
-You're a middle-aged widow.
-I'm not that old.

186
00:10:51,534 --> 00:10:53,627
Not some trollop
out of a Jackie Collins novel.

187
00:10:53,803 --> 00:10:56,772
There's no reason to be absolutely ugly
to me in front of people.

188
00:10:56,939 --> 00:11:00,067
I'm trying to protect you. What if
it doesn't work out, like the last one?

189
00:11:00,242 --> 00:11:02,642
I couldn't bear to see you get hurt again.

190
00:11:02,812 --> 00:11:07,340
You know something, we never regret
the things that we actually do in our lives...

191
00:11:07,516 --> 00:11:10,417
...only the things that we don't do. So.

192
00:11:10,586 --> 00:11:13,111
Where did you get
that pseudo-philosophical platitude?

193
00:11:13,289 --> 00:11:15,120
-It doesn't matter.
-Dr. Phil?

194
00:11:15,291 --> 00:11:17,987
Okay, that's not funny.
I think I'm gonna go.

195
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:20,128
Okay, fine.

196
00:11:20,296 --> 00:11:23,459
So. When is this date?

197
00:11:24,133 --> 00:11:28,035
-Friday night.
-What? That's Putt-Putt night.

198
00:11:28,204 --> 00:11:31,799
JAN: But I said I was sorry.
-Well, I'm afraid sorry won't do.

199
00:11:31,974 --> 00:11:34,408
I know, I know, sweetheart.

200
00:11:34,577 --> 00:11:38,775
What if I make your favorite, huh?
What do you think? Little bitty?

201
00:11:38,948 --> 00:11:41,212
No! You can't win back my affection
with Manwich.

202
00:11:41,384 --> 00:11:44,285
This has been the worst day of my life.
I'm going to my room.

203
00:12:27,663 --> 00:12:30,188
JEFFREY:
Did you do something to your hair?

204
00:12:30,366 --> 00:12:32,129
JAN:
I cut it.

205
00:12:34,503 --> 00:12:37,995
A little garish,
but not altogether unattractive.

206
00:12:38,174 --> 00:12:41,666
-Really?
-What's the occasion?

207
00:12:41,844 --> 00:12:44,506
Well, I have a date tonight, remember?

208
00:12:45,381 --> 00:12:47,941
Oh, yes, right, of course.

209
00:12:48,117 --> 00:12:51,245
The bitter sting of rejection's
coming back to me now.

210
00:12:51,420 --> 00:12:54,253
Jeffrey. Oh, my goodness, here it is.

211
00:12:54,423 --> 00:12:55,856
Well, have a nice day.

212
00:12:56,025 --> 00:12:58,516
-Aren't you forgetting something?
-What?

213
00:12:58,694 --> 00:13:01,629
It comes in a brown paper sack,
and rhymes with my lunch.

214
00:13:01,797 --> 00:13:03,958
I just didn't have time
to make it this morning.

215
00:13:04,133 --> 00:13:07,660
Why can't you just grab yourself
a little sandwich or something?

216
00:13:07,837 --> 00:13:11,534
All right, honey? Bye-bye, bye-bye.
There you go.

217
00:13:27,990 --> 00:13:28,979
[SIGHS]

218
00:13:29,158 --> 00:13:31,126
Can I help you?

219
00:13:32,862 --> 00:13:35,956
Yes. Do you have anything
that's not utterly repugnant?

220
00:13:36,131 --> 00:13:37,393
No.

221
00:13:39,168 --> 00:13:40,999
Okay.

222
00:13:41,170 --> 00:13:44,799
Fine, give me three biscottis...

223
00:13:44,974 --> 00:13:47,135
...two chocolate chip fudge brownies...

224
00:13:47,309 --> 00:13:50,039
...and one of these giant
Rice Krispie abominations.

225
00:13:50,212 --> 00:13:52,180
Maybe a heart attack will teach
my mother...

226
00:13:52,348 --> 00:13:55,340
-...a lesson in abandonment.
-Maybe.

227
00:13:55,985 --> 00:13:57,748
Biscotti.

228
00:14:00,890 --> 00:14:02,289
That's a cool store.

229
00:14:02,458 --> 00:14:07,088
It's actually got some character,
unlike those lame mega-chains.

230
00:14:07,263 --> 00:14:08,821
Do you like working there?

231
00:14:08,998 --> 00:14:12,331
It's paying the bills
until I make my first astronomical discovery.

232
00:14:12,501 --> 00:14:16,164
You're an astronomer?
That's cool.

233
00:14:16,772 --> 00:14:20,208
I'm a singer, actually. Well, trying to be.

234
00:14:21,110 --> 00:14:23,044
Most of my songs
that I write are about...

235
00:14:23,212 --> 00:14:26,204
...how corporate America's
totally screwing up our culture.

236
00:14:26,382 --> 00:14:29,146
I'm calling my first album
"Bed, Bath and Bullshit."

237
00:14:29,318 --> 00:14:30,649
So....

238
00:14:30,819 --> 00:14:35,085
I actually do a show here every Saturday.

239
00:14:36,025 --> 00:14:39,290
It's not sappy. You know,
my songs aren't about love or anything.

240
00:14:39,461 --> 00:14:41,395
They're about...

241
00:14:41,564 --> 00:14:44,431
...how much I hate corporations.

242
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:49,196
